@node Installation "DigiCam: Installation"

                                  Installation
                                 --------------

- copy DigiCam anywhere in your path

- copy DigiCam.guide wherever you can retrieve it.

- I suggest adding an alias to your s:shell-startup, just to avoid typing to
  much, e.g. 'alias dc DigiCam serial.device 0 230400'

@endnode


@node Usage "DigiCam: Usage"

                                     Usage
                                    -------

   What I will give you here is a brief description of all options.
   In advance, DigiCam is dumb but flexible :)

   Every settings of the camera e.g. resolution, are as numbers. The
   numbers are directly send to the camera. There is no interpretation done,
   so if you want a particular resolution you can't say: I want 'HI', you 
   have to say: I want '5' (or wahtever).
   The representation of the numbers seems to vary much between the different
   cameras. At least the Sanyo VPC-X350EX differs from the protocol description
   in some points.

   To understand every option, you really should get the protocol-description
   from Eugene Crosser: http://www.average.org/DigiCam/protocol.html

   The always needed basics: DEVICE UNIT BPS
   e.g. DigiCam serial.device 0  230400

   DigiCam should supports any serial-driver, was tested on Amiga's internal
   serial port and a MultiFaceIII.
   Settings the BPS to 230400 is not a joke. The maximum speed for the Sanyo is
   230400 and my Amiga (Cyberstorm MK1 060/50MHz) managed it well to get that
   rate at his internal port using the standard serial.device as well as
   8n1.device or artser.device. It is true that the communication was only
   errorfree if I let my Amiga completely alone during transfers. But since
   errors are detected and damaged packets are rerequested by the camera,
   using 230400 with some resends is possible and still much faster than 115200.

   DigiCam supports upto 460800, untested.

   In cases DigiCam seems to hang, wait some time because there should be a
   watchdog timeout everywhere.
   The longest timeout is cameradependent and takes 45 secs on the Sanyo.
   Rebooting the Amiga is probably the faster solution then ...

   Commands can be nested but not repeated and are executed in a fixed order.
   1. all settings/registers are set, 2. info, 3. any eraseprocedure,
   4. takepicture/preview, 5. download
   e.g. DigiCam serial.device 0 230400 nametosave ERASEALL TP GF=1 DIR


      @{" General Options  " link GeneralO}
      @{" Downloading      " link DownloadingO}
      @{" Erasing          " link ErasingO}
      @{" Actions          " link ActionsO}
      @{" Settings         " link SettingsO}
      @{" Special Funtions " link SpecialsO}

@endnode

@node GeneralO "DigiCam: General Options"

                                General Options
                               -----------------

   INFO
   Writes some info about the camera, if some "denied by camera" occur don't
   be afraid.

   DIR
   Lists the pictures and animations stored in the camera, here you can also
   spy out the numbers matching the resolutions.

@endnode

@node DownloadingO "DigiCam: Downloading"

                                  Downloading
                                 -------------

   GF=GETFRAME       downloads picture(s), format: jpeg (little strange,
                     some datatypes won't display 'em).

   GAT=GETFRAMETHUMB downloads the preview of a picture.

   GA=GETANIM        downloads anims, format: AVI, can be played by e.g. CyberAVI.

   GAT=GETANIMTHUMB  downloads the preview of an anim.

   GU=GETAUDIO       downloads audiocomments from picture, format: WAV:

   You can give a single one e.g. GF=11, ranges GF=1-10 and all, e.g. GF=All
   A filename is always needed, the filename is expanded by the type of the 
   download and the frame/animnumber.

   Download has a progress display, every dot represents a 2KB package, every
   exclamation mark a damaged, rerequested one.

@endnode

@node ErasingO "DigiCam: Erasing"

                                    Erasing
                                   ---------


   You can ERASEALL, ERASELAST or ERF=ERASEFRAME or ERA=ERASEANIM, single,
   range or all.
   Please note ERASEALL is not equal to ERASEFRAME=ALL, because ERASEALL is a
   single command and surely faster, but erases only frames as well.

@endnode

@node ActionsO "DigiCam: Actions"

                                    Actions
                                   ---------

   TP=TAKEPICTURE  Takes a picture, just as pressing the release button.
                   DELAY can be used to set a delay in seconds for the
                   picture. The picture is stored in the camera.

   MP=MAKEPREVIEW  downloads a live-picture from the camera in a
                   fixed standardresolution.

   ST=SETTIME      Sets the cameratime to the current time of your Amiga.

@endnode

@node SettingsO "DigiCam: Settings"


                                    Settings
                                   ----------

   All arguments are numbers, availability is modeldependent, some maybe
   read-only (shown in INFO).
   All numbers and its representations are taken from the protocoldescription.
   It is always possible that there are different or more selections
   available.

   RES=RESOLUTION You should take picture in every resolution your camera is
                  capable of and spy the numbers out with DIR.

   SH=SHUTTERSPEED In microsecs.

   FM=FLASHMODE 0 Auto, 1 Force, 2 Off, 3 Anti RedEye, 4 SlowSync.

   AP=APERTURE 1 Low, 2 Mid, 3 Hi.

   CM=COLORMODE 1 Color, 2 B/W.

   LS=LCDSHUT Autoshuttime for the LCD in Secs.

   ASH=AUTOSHUTHOST Autoshuttime for camera if connected to a Computer
                    in secs.

   ASH=AUTOSHUTHOSTFIELD Autoshuttime for camera if single in secs.

   LM=LENSMODE 1 Macro, 2 Normal, 3 Infinity/Fisheye, e.g. read-only on
               the Sanyo, because the mode is mechanically switched.

   BM=BITMAP 1 AEL/WBL, 2 Fisheye, 4 Wide, 8 Digital Zoom, 16 B/W.

   EXP=EXPMETER 2 Center weighted, 3 Spot, 5 Multi element matrix.

   BC=BRIGTHNESSCONTR 0 Normal, 1 Bright+, 2 Bright-, 3 Contrast+,
                      4 Contrast-.

   WB=WHITEBALANCE 0 Auto, 1 Skylight, 2 Fluorescent, 3 Tungsten, 255 Cloudy.

   LD=LCDDATEFORMAT 1 YY/MM/DD, 2 DD/MM/HH, 3 DD/MM/YY

   LB=LCDBRIGHTNESS 1 to 7 maybe more

@endnode

@node SpecialsO "DigiCam: Special Functions"

                               Special Functions
                              -------------------

   These functions are to explore a camera, the search of new features.
   Note: Reading registers in a way there aren't meant may hang up the
         camera.
   Reading vdata-registers as int32-registers seems to be secure, if not
   done in to fast sequence.
   Reading int32-registers as vdata let the Sanyo hang up several time,
   using ranges while using READDATA is not safe.

   The Sanyo mostly resets itself after 45 seconds, but sometimes it das
   necessary to plug off the serial cable at the camera. Closing the shutter
   (switching it off) didn't help.


   RI=READINTREG single (RI=10) or range (RI=2-12). Tries to read the
                 registers as int32 and shows the result if possible.
                 Is intentionally slow for ranges, faster progress
                 worried the Sanyo.
                 Result is a number.

   RD=READDATA   single (RD=46) or range (RD=46-47). Tries to read the
                 registers as int32 and shows the result if possible.
                 Result is a hexdump and all readable characters.

   SI=SETINT     Allows you to set an int32-register with the value.
   V=VALUE       e.g. SI=7 V=0
                 Please be careful using this option, you never know
                 what can be screwed up by hitting unknown registers.

   TA=TAKEACTION Allows you to send an action command to the camera
                 the argument send to the camera is value.
                 e.g. TA=2 V=0 takes a picture

@endnode

